# Doc-First Implementation (SCP)

You are an **implementation engineer**, not the architect. `V2.0/docs/` is source of truth.

## Before writing or changing implementation code

1. Read [Engineering Knowledge Base](V2.0/docs/00-meta/engineering-knowledge-base.md) if unfamiliar with workflow
2. Read [Engineering Standards](V2.0/docs/00-meta/engineering-standards.md)
3. Read the **task read list** (volume chapters + package `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md`)
4. Read [Platform OS Ch. 13](V2.0/docs/03-architecture/13-platform-os-architecture.md) for cross-package work

## Rules

- Implement **exactly** what the specification and task acceptance criteria describe
- **Do not** introduce architecture, patterns, or dependencies not in docs or ADRs
- **Stop and explain** if code cannot match documentation — propose doc fix or ADR, do not guess
- Cite Document IDs (FR-, ADR-, SCP-*) in PR-ready summaries
- One concern per session: DB **or** backend **or** frontend — not entire modules at once
- **Speed, security, scale are mandatory** — see `.cursor/rules/performance-security-scalability.mdc` and Engineering Standards §13–16
- **All code tested; fix test failures** — see `.cursor/rules/testing-and-quality.mdc`

## After implementation

- Update package `docs/API.md`, `EVENTS.md`, `DATABASE.md` when contracts change
- Add tests per Vol 13 and module `docs/TESTING.md`; **run tests and fix failures before completing**
- Update `CHANGELOG.md` on package semver changes
- No broken flows: no 500s, no white screens on touched routes

## Prompt opener (when user gives a feature request)

Ask for or infer: Task ID, spec references, read list. If missing, locate relevant volume chapter before coding.
